cmake-update-lists.py

A tiny utility to sort, clean and rewrite SRCS and HDRS lists in marked CMakeLists.txt files. You can run this utility from any directory.

If rewritten file does not differ from the original, original file remains untouched. Otherwise, original file is saved to CMakeLists.txt.orig and the rewritten file substitutes previous one.

Introducing TCP stack for YT

This is a huge 'merge' commit of branch babenko/tcp.
Some highlights:

* Introduce delay between voting rounds
* Use LastSystemError and LastSystemErrorText from Arcadia
* Set SO_REUSEADDR option
* Copy libuv during prepare
* Try to open client socket of appropriate type
* Open server socket in event thread
* Disable Nagle
* Handle bus creation errors
* Another try/catch to ignore IO errors during procfs lookup
* Increase buffer size to 16Kb
* Call accept in a loop
* Replaced some * by ptrs
* Setting ulimit -n 4096 for ytserver
* Execute socket reads and socket writes in a loop
* Enable libev backends for win32
* Trying to fix stalled connections
* Removed nonexisting file
* Don't update the watcher for closed connection
* Don't do anything for closed sockets
* Check for pending write range when updating socket watcher
* Make a copy of Connections before iterating
* Enable large chunk optimization
* Switching small chunk optimization off
* Only enable TRACE for debug builds
* Added missing out_throughput profiling
* Tcp statistics and throttling
* Set request info
* Use EscapeYPathToken for profiling paths
* rpc_timeout -> supervisor_rpc_timeout
* Decrease pressure when packets are cleaned up
* More supervisor_rpc_timeout changes
* SO_PRIORITY support
* Use connection priorities
* Switched low-level diagnostics to trace
* TRACE level now only available for debug builds (by default)
* Changed connection counting strategy
* Break cyclic references (session <-> bus)
* Enable Scalar(size_t) for Mac
* Refactoring job specs, step 1: added Ext suffixes, moved output_transaction_id to the outer spec.
* Refactoring job specs, step 2: moved input_specs and output_specs to TJobSpec.

simple c++ lambda support for some yt operations Add a way to express some YT operations with c++ lambdas (only those without captures, i.e. equivalent to plain C function pointers). Currently available: * CopyIf - copy records on whose the predicate is TRUE from src to dst table * Map - transform records from src to dst * AdditiveMapReduce - transform records using 1st lambda, sum them using 2nd lambda * AdditiveMapReduceSorted - same as AdditiveMapReduce, but the table is sorted after MR. More operations will probably follow. When these functions are used with protobuf output, they also add schema to output tables (using table_schema library). add more MapReduce operations in c++ lambda form MapReduce[Sorted] - transform records using 1st lambda, reduce them using 2nd lambda, then (optionally) transform again to output format using 3rd lambda (finalizer). MapReduceCombined[Sorted] - transform records using 1st lambda (mapper), reduce them first time using 2nd lambda (combiner), sum (reduce second time) them using 3rd lambda (reducer), (optionally) transform again to output format using 4th lambda (finalizer). Unlike AdditiveMapReduce, these functions allow reducing to different type. Additionally, data accumulated by reducer need not to be final, it can be transformed once again by an additional lambda, "finalizer". This allows more generic processing, e.g. calculate a dispersion. Since reducer is not associative now, it can't be used quietly as combiner. Therefore MapReduceCombined functions accept yet one more lambda, the combiner. This new code keeps previous approach that reducer lambda must not work with key fields, even at some cost in performance. Since types are different, wrapper now copies whose fields explicitly, using new TFieldCopier class. YT-9521

Fast cluster node selection by (DC, medium) in TChunkPlacement.

TChunkPlacement used to index cluster nodes by medium. This made
selecting nodes limited to specific data centers slow.

Now cluster nodes are indexed by (DC, medium) pairs. This is
implemented by storing fill- and load-factor maps separately for each
such pair. When selecting nodes from multiple data centers,
corresponding maps are merged on the fly.

As an added benefit, selecting the maps to merge is now the only place
where DCs are actually used during a call to AllocateWriteTargets. In
other words, we never look into individual nodes' DC because the nodes
are already partitioned by them.

For consistency, the same pattern was applied to media: all the
medium-related checks (is the medium cache? does the node even has
this medium?) are factored out and performed only when a node is (or
isn't) placed into a partition. Once it's there, AllocateWriteTargets
doesn't have to concern itself with media that much - it must only
select the right partitions.

The above doesn't apply to preffered hosts - they may come not from
load factor maps but elsewhere and thus may be unvetted. Therefore
media and DC are still checked explicitly for preffered nodes.

c++ lambda: save/load global user settings Because our lambdas can not have capture list, provide a way to have configurable settings using global variables. Those variables must be specially marked to get saved and loaded by lambda wrapers. Two ways are currently provided: 1. Inherit from ISerializableForJob, use Y_SAVELOAD_JOB macro and register with RegisterGlobalSaveable. 2. Declare variable as TSaveable<YourOriginalClass> and use Y_SAVELOAD_DEFINE (TSaveable will register itself). 2a. For simplier types, use TSaveablePOD<YourStruct>, no Y_SAVELOAD_DEFINE needed (will also register itself).

Introduce the "externalize_lb.py" script.

The script automates several steps needed to (relatively) safely
externalize a directory. In particular:
  - closing the directory down (via ACL) for the duration of the
    process so as to not take the data under LB's feet - and opening
    it up afterwards;
  - aborting transactions in the directory;
  - externalization per se.

In addition, preliminary checks are performed for some pitfalls (like
attempting to externalize a symlink) and common hindrances that would
prevent externalization from succeeding (like non-external tables or
symlinks that cross the would-be portal boundary).

YT-12678: Remove MultiReader inheritance Теперь сущность, которая занимается асинхронным управлением ридеров, называется MultiReaderManager и хранится как поле внутри мультиридеров. Добавлен интерфейс **IMultiReaderManager**, классы **TMultiReaderManagerBase**, **TSequentialMultiReaderManager**, **TParallelMultiReaderManager** разнесены по разным cpp файлам и спрятаны за креейтерами. Убрано наследование от менеджера в следующих мультиридерах: - TFileMultiChunkReader - TPartitionMultiChunkReader - TSchemalessMultiChunkReader - TMultiChunkReaderMock Следующим, последним шагом, добавлю логику асинхронного добавления ридеров в MultiChunkReader. YT-12963: Sharded transactions Transactions are now coordinated by a (configurable) set of master cells. That is, at the start of a transaction, a coordinator cell is chosen (randomly), and that particular transaction is started there. (Instead of always starting at the primary cell.) Moreover, at the moment of its start, a transaction is no longer replicated to other cells (at least, not by default). Instead, it is replicated on demand, later (if ever). Executing a transactional request now involves the additional step of replicating transactions (or making sure they've been replicated earlier) to the cell of execution. (A transactional request is a request that has specified either a transaction to execute within or at least one prerequisite transaction, or both.) This additional replication step is taken for: - ObjectService's Execute request (unless suppress_transaction_coordinator_sync is specified); - ChunkService's ExecuteBatch method; - TransactionSupervisor's CommitTransaction method (for prerequisites only).

Separate LSM algorithm and application Introduced server/lib/lsm, a separate place for all LSM algorithms. Now the algorithms operate over standalone classes (NLsm::TTablet, NLsm::TPartition, NLsm::TStore) and produce a set of actions that are later materialized and applied to the real-world objects by old TStoreCompactor and friends. Brief description of new classes and responsibilities: - NTabletNode::TLsmInterop: converts real-world objects (tablets, partitions, stores) to NLsm classes, calls the algorithm, sends the actions to compactor, partition balancer etc. - NTabletNode::TStoreCompactor, NTabletNode::TPartitionBalancer etc: actually perform compactions/splits/merges prescribed by the tasks. Note that now they work in the "push" model instead of the "pull" one, receiving actions instead of scanning slots themselves. These classes also validate actions: e.g. the action may try to operate over a tablet that was already unmounted, or a store to compact was removed by a concurrent process. - NLsm::TStoreCompactor, NLsm::TPartitionBalancer etc: algorithm details. All decisions on what to compact and how to compact are made there. - NLsm::TLsmBackend: helper that wraps all underlying algorithms and serves as a single entry point for the TLsmInterop. TStoreCompactor still bears responsibility for parts of the algorithm: e.g. it choses the order to perform compaction tasks. This commit involves only store compactor and partition balancer, other parts of the LSM will be migrated later. The algorithms did not change, though the order in which validation is performed has changed. As a result, in some corner- cases compaction and partition balancing tasks may be executed in different order than before.

YT-13943: schema objects Schemas have been transformed into full-fledged objects. Unlike objects of other types, schemas live only as long as they are referenced by tables or, in rarer cases, transactions. The only exception to this is the builtin empty schema object which is always present, with its reference at least 1. (Otherwise, empty schema object is treated exatly as any other schema object.) Schema objects differ from objects of other types in another way: they are cell-local. That it, every master cell has a separate set of schemas, with diferring IDs and everything. Cross-cell copying is supported, but will result in two equivalent schemas with distinct IDs. However, because object ID comprises cell tag, schema IDs will never clash. In other words: - different schemas are guaranteed to have distinct IDs; - different IDs do not necessarily refer to different schemas.

YTORM-47: ORM master + RPC proxy = <3 ORM master при старте транзакции принимает underlying transaction id. Если id непуст, берет underlying transaction из общего с RPC proxy пула, а не создает сам. Такими транзакциями ORM master не владет, как следствие при Commit он не зовет Commit таких транзакций, а просто флашит свои изменения в них. Discovery collocated proxies пока производится через ORM master discovery. В перспективе будет поддержан механизм на основе Кипариса, как с обычными RPC proxies. Изменения большие: - API service полностью уехал в общую либу - Security manager полностью уехал в общую либу - IAccessChecker уехал в общую либу вместе с no-op реализацией. Содержательная реализация осталась на прежнем месте Изменения небольшие: - TraceSampler уехал из proxy coordinator в bootstrap, там же подписывается на dynamic config update как и остальные компоненты - Как следствие proxy coordinator не требует bootstrap на входе и Initialize, являет собой простым хранителем информации о доступности и живости прокси - Discovery service стал чище: GrpcProxyPath_ константный, нет метода Initialize наравне с флажком Initialized_, не имеющим к методу отношения - Security manager: подчистились includes, больше не хранит bootstrap, добавился logger

New P2P - Решение о применении P2P становится синхронным. Нода не даст читать блок больше N раз за окно. Эвристика не опирается на общий трафик на ноде и смотрит только на число запросов к чанку/блоку. - P2P блоки на пире хранятся в отдельном кеше. Это должно починить проблему с вымыванием, и позволит лучше мониторить работу всей конструкции. - Троттлер для исходящего трафика не нужен, потому что P2P не может генерировать трафика больше чем 1/N от исходного. - Старый код остался и пока включен по дефолту. Consistent chunk replica placement support (a.k.a. CRP). At chunk creation, an optional ui64 hash may be provided. A chunk with such a hash will be placed on cluster nodes consistently: two chunks with equal hashes will end up on same nodes. Some design considerations follow. The consistent hashing rings are per-medium. In order to optimize the number of replicas to relocate on a node outage, multiple "tokens" are placed on the ring for each cluster node. The number of tokens is determined by building a coarse-grained histogram of nodes by their disk capacity. A nice-and-tidy theory of a consistent hashing ring algorithm is somewhat hindered by the harsh reality, making straightforward application impossible. First of all, hash collisions would lead to placing multiple replicas of a chunk on the same node which is unacceptable. Second of all, there's rack awareness and similar constraints. To deal with this, a concept of "sufficiently large replica count" is introduced. Placing, say, a hundred chunk "replicas" on the ring produces a hundred candidate nodes. The hope is that, among those, there will be enough nodes to both avoid clashes and satisfy rack awareness constraints. To minimize the number of items on the ring, chunks are combined into so-called placement groups. Chunks with the same hash and medium belong to the same group.

Support snapshot dowloading for Hydra v2. Snapshot downloading is now supported for remote stores, too (in addition to already being supported for local stores). The code relies on ISnapshot{Store,Reader,Writer} interfaces only and is thus oblivious to particular store implementations. The new downloading code utilizes RPC streaming (because why not). YT-17406: introduce YPath attribute filter. Lots of preliminary refactorings; no visible effects are expected yet. TAttributeFilter is an extension of former TAttributeKeys. In addition to specifying top-level attribute keys, TAttributeFilter supports specifying a list of YPaths allowing filtration of nested subtrees. This commit does not add support of path filtration anywhere; it will be added in commits yet to follow. A list of interface changes: - NYTree.NProto.TAttributeKeys is renamed to NYTree.TAttributeFilter and is extended with `paths` field. - Driver commands are able to deserialize attribute filter from a legacy "string list" form as well as from a modern "map with `keys` and `paths`" form in wire-protocol compatible manner. - NRpcProxy.NProto.TAttributeKeys is renamed to TLegacyAttributeKeys. - A "universal filter" value for TAttributeFilter is encoded as protobuf absense. This contrasts with TLegacyAttributeKeys which contains "boolean all" denoting universal filter. - A `TAttributeFilter attributes` field is added to TReq{Get,List}{Node,Job[s],Operation[s]}. - A legacy form of specifying attributes is left for the RPC requests above for the sake of compatibility. - A modern field is preferred to a legacy field in case both of them are specified. - C++ & Go RPC clients specify attributes both in legacy and modern forms for compatibility with older RPC proxies; this should be eliminated after all clusters are 22.3+. - Java client specifies only in legacy form (as I was too lazy to fix that).

YT-17408 Allow http client to reuse connections Implemented http connection pool with LRU-like behaviour. Also there is helper wrapper `TConnectionReuseWrapper`, which is used to wrap all connection's users in order to collect information about possibility to use the connection again. The information is stored in `TReusableConnectionState`. When the destructor of shared state is called, the connection considered free and can be returned to the pool, depending on collected information. Implemented `TMultiLruCache` that supports storing of items with equal keys. Find on such key returns least recently used item from the cache.

New scripts for building and deploying python packages Usage: ``` cd /path/to/arcadia/yt/python/packages/deploy ya make ./deploy_python_package ARGUMENTS ``` OR (for open source) ``` ./doall.py ARGUMENTS ``` Arguments: - `--arcadia-root /path/to/arcdaia` - required - `--package PACKAGE` - required, package to build (for example, yandex-yt-python) - `--yt-path relative/path/to/yt` - defaults to yt/ - `--package-type TYPE` - one of {pypi,debian,all}, defaults to all - `--deploy | --no-deploy` - whether to deploy built packages, defaults to true - `--work-dir /path/to/work/dir` - particular working directory, otherwise temp dir will be created - `--repos REPOS` - list of repositories to upload built debian package - `--already-prepared` - whether a source tree in the working directory is already prepared - `-v` - additional logs For more options see `--help`

Request queue provider is now an interface (as opposed to a simple callback).

Subsequently to provider returning a particular queue for the first time,
that queue is configured by the RPC service code using that service's config
for the corresponding method. This may not be sufficient, however, as the
queue provider may require additional configuration (which it cannot apply
at the time of queue construction as any such configuration will be
overwritten by the aforementioned mechanism). Introducing IRequestQueueProvider
solves this problem by providing explicit customization point in the form of
the 'ConfigureQueue' method.

YT-15962: Add chunk schemas

ORIGINAL PR: https://a.yandex-team.ru/review/2271305/details

This PR refactors / adds several things, namely:
1) Adds chunk schemas
2) Makes master table schemas hold strong refs to the accounts that use it
3) And provides optimizations around schemas fetch in controller agents

In details:
1) Logic behind their creation is simple: if schema for chunk is not specified, then we should use a schema provided by the table to which this chunk is going to be attached to.
Iff chunk schema differs from table's, then create it. Unfortunately creating it is not a very simple process; to ensure that chunk's native cell controls the lifetime of an associated schema, first we need to deliver said schema to the cell, temporarily attach it to a transaction, and then recreate it as a local object. In order to send as little information as possible, in most places schema is identified by it's id. It's attached to a chunk when chunk gets confirmed.

2) Self explanatory, but I will  specify none the less. Previously every schema saved a raw pointer to an account whenever said account would become an owner of a table. Now, this is changed to a master smart pointer to an account, which is, in essence, a strong ref.

3) Because schemas are now being exported to other cell tags it's no longer required to fetch everything from the native (which usually is primary) cell. This functionality is only partially enabled as of now, because I fear that enabling this many features all at once will make it impossible to debug anything without going completely insane.

YT-20218: Cosmetic fixes

In response to commentaries in https://a.yandex-team.ru/review/4636903.

Active spinlock tracking from pr3151306. Added TracelessGuards to disable mentioned tracking

1) Добавлена возможность инструментировать ваш любимый мьютекс/спинлок/что-либо с методами Acquire/Release со схожим смыслом. Делается это засчет методов ```NThreading::NDetail::RecordSpinlockAcquired```/```NThreading::NDetail::RecordSpinlockReleased```. Они отслеживают число захваченных спинлоков.

2) Добавлен макрос ```REGISTER_TRACKED_SPIN_LOCK_CLASS```, который позволяет номинально проверить на этапе компиляции, что данный спинлок отслеживается.

3) Добавлен метод ```NThreading::VerifyNoSpinlockAffinity```, который коркается, если число захваченных спинлоков больше нуля.

4) Добавлены Traceless версии (почти) всех гардов, чтобы можно было не отслеживать конкретную критическую секцию, если очень нужно.

5) Внутри файберного ```WaitUntilSet``` вызывается ```VerifyNoSpinlockAffinity``` -- делать ```WaitFor``` или ```Yield``` внутри отслеживаемых критических секций нельзя. Если очень хочется -- используем TracelessGuard нужного вида.

6) Теперь отслеживаются такие спинлоки и их наследники: ```TSpinLock```, ```TRecursiveSpinLock```, ```TReaderWriterSpinLock```.

7) Зарегистрированы как отслеживаемые все вышеперечисленные спинлоки и их Padded версии.

8) Все эти действия имеют эффект только в дебаг сборке. В релизе вся эта диагностика стирается.

# О чем этот PR?
Добавляем возможность автоматического запуска Clang Static Analyzer (CSA) при сборке бинарников
# Уже же есть clang tidy зачем нам еще и clang static analyzer?
Да, clang tidy включает в себя возможности static analyzer, но данный PR расширает возможности CSA, а конкретно:
1. Фильтрация анализируемых файлов -- CSA по дефолту такое делать не умеет, а стандартные чекеры находят всякий мусор в либах контриба
2. Возможность подгружать свои собственные плагины -- они же чекеры
# А нам точно нужен CSA?
Да, нужен, так как он находит провисшие ссылки https://a.yandex-team.ru/review/4679116/details -- проезды по памяти ловить ооочень сложно

YT-14965: Allow serialization by traits

```yt/core``` contains a bunch of configs which are pod structs. Let's say ```TConfig``` is one of them.

**Previously**:

There is a ```TSerializableConfig``` struct which is a ```TYsonStruct```. It has ```Register``` method which has all relevant serialization info.

If your serializable class needs ```TConfig``` field you have to include header containing ```TSerializableConfig``` and use ```TSerializableConfigPtr``` or ```TSerializableConfig``` field instead depending on whether it is ```TYsonStruct``` or a  ```TYsonStructLite```.

You have to upcast ```TSerializableConfigPtr``` to ```TConfig``` if you need the underlying object.

You can use ```TSerializableConfigPtr``` however you want (e.g. inherit from it).

**Now**:

There is a ```TConfigSerializer``` struct which is ```TExternalizedYsonStruct<TConfig>```. It has ```Register``` method which has all relevant serialization info.

If your serializable class needs ```TConfig``` field you have to include header containing ```TConfigSerializer``` and use ```TConfig``` field as is.

Failing to include header containing ```TConfigSerializer``` will result in compilation error "No matching call to function Serialize (or Deserialize)".

You are not supposed to interact with ```TConfigSerializer``` in any way.

Inheriting from ```TConfig``` is not natively supported -- you have to write base parameters serialization manually.

**Current configs status**:

So far only ```TExponentinalBackoffOptions``` and ```TConstantBackoffOptions``` are rewritten this way.
